<span id="freeTextContainer14772503883697015140">In the 20-year history of our book club, one devoted to reading classics and Pulitzer and Nobel prize winning lit., we rarely have one that has brought as much acclaim as this book. Several of us had read the book and recommended it for years. The outdated title was off-putting to the other group members. They were all pleasantly astounded and still recommend it to any newcomers that attend our group with misty eyed fondness. Perhaps the title, which uses religious references that are not played</span>
  <span id="freeText14772503883697015140" style="display:none">In the 20-year history of our book club, one devoted to reading classics and Pulitzer and Nobel prize winning lit., we rarely have one that has brought as much acclaim as this book. Several of us had read the book and recommended it for years. The outdated title was off-putting to the other group members. They were all pleasantly astounded and still recommend it to any newcomers that attend our group with misty eyed fondness. Perhaps the title, which uses religious references that are not played out in a major way in the book, not to mention the archaic word "bosom," should be changed to make the book more assessable today. I am not sure what I would call it if I were in charge of the new title, other than "wonderful!" </span>
