<span id="freeTextContainer14948786086402146727">This is a very powerful and beautifully-written book about rural Georgia in the 1800s. (It was Margaret Mitchell&apos;s favorite book!) If you are interested in American history, especially historical fiction about the antebellum South, check this out. (Some of the characters&apos; ways of thinking are backward and offensive by our standards, especially regarding racial issues, but it is a book about uneducated people from a time long ago, and it can be valuable to see how far we&apos;ve come racially, sociall</span>
  <span id="freeText14948786086402146727" style="display:none">This is a very powerful and beautifully-written book about rural Georgia in the 1800s. (It was Margaret Mitchell's favorite book!) If you are interested in American history, especially historical fiction about the antebellum South, check this out. (Some of the characters' ways of thinking are backward and offensive by our standards, especially regarding racial issues, but it is a book about uneducated people from a time long ago, and it can be valuable to see how far we've come racially, socially, medically [if you cut your foot back then and got an infection, you basically died], and in so many other ways. It's definitely better to live in our time than in any other.) This book won a Pulitzer and as sometimes happens, I'm glad I read it just because it won a Pulitzer. I've read quite a few fantastic books just because they won a Newbery, too. DON'T read only books that won one of these two awards, but DEFINITELY mix some in!</span>
